  <h2>A New Regulatory Architecture</h2>

  <p>The Cambodia Gaming Commission (CGC) has unveiled a comprehensive three-tier licensing framework for offshore and online gaming operators, marking the most significant regulatory initiative in Cambodia's gaming sector since the country began attracting operators from neighboring jurisdictions. The framework, which takes effect immediately with a 180-day compliance window, is explicitly designed to bring order to an industry segment that has grown rapidly but largely without formal regulatory structure.</p>

  <p>The timing is not coincidental. Since the Philippines enacted its POGO ban in late 2024, an estimated 40 to 60 offshore gaming firms have relocated their operations to Cambodia, primarily establishing bases in Phnom Penh and Sihanoukville. These operators, which previously held PAGCOR-issued offshore gaming licenses, serve international player markets, predominantly in China and other Asian countries. Their migration created both an economic opportunity and a regulatory challenge for Cambodia.</p>

  <p>"Cambodia cannot afford to become a haven for unregulated gaming," said a CGC spokesperson in a briefing attended by international media. "This framework establishes clear rules, meaningful capital requirements, and enforcement mechanisms. Operators who comply will have a legitimate path forward. Those who do not will face criminal prosecution."</p>

  <h2>The Three-Tier System</h2>

  <p>The licensing framework is structured into three tiers, differentiated by capital requirements, employee thresholds, annual license fees, and operational scope. The tiered approach is designed to accommodate operators of varying scale while ensuring that all licensees meet minimum regulatory standards.</p>

