  <h2>The 180-Day Compliance Deadline</h2>

  <p>All operators currently conducting gaming activities in Cambodia without a CGC license have 180 days from the framework's effective date to submit a complete license application, satisfy capital requirements, and demonstrate compliance with the applicable regulatory standards. The CGC has indicated that it will begin processing applications immediately, with the goal of issuing the first licenses within 90 days.</p>

  <p>The 180-day window is designed to be realistic but firm. Operators that fail to apply or that are denied a license must cease operations by the deadline. The CGC has stated that it will coordinate with Cambodia's Ministry of Interior and national police to enforce the compliance deadline, including shutting down unlicensed operations and pursuing criminal charges against operators who continue to operate illegally.</p>

  <h2>Criminal Penalties: A Deterrent Framework</h2>

  <p>The enforcement provisions of the new framework are notably severe. Operating an unlicensed gaming business in Cambodia after the 180-day compliance period will carry criminal penalties of up to 10 years imprisonment and fines of up to $250,000. These penalties apply to both corporate officers and individuals who facilitate unlicensed gaming operations.</p>

  <p>The severity of the penalties reflects Cambodia's awareness that its gaming sector has attracted international scrutiny. Reports of human trafficking, forced labor, and financial crime connected to unregulated gaming compounds in Sihanoukville and other locations have generated negative headlines and prompted diplomatic pressure from China, the Philippines, and international organizations.</p>

  <h2>FATF-Aligned AML Requirements</h2>

  <p>A central pillar of the new framework is the integration of anti-money laundering (AML) requirements aligned with Financial Action Task Force (FATF) standards. Cambodia has been under increased FATF scrutiny in recent years, and the gaming sector has been identified as a key vulnerability. The licensing framework addresses this by mandating:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Customer due diligence (CDD):</strong> All tiers must implement identity verification for players, with enhanced due diligence required for Tier 2 and Tier 3 operators.</li>
    <li><strong>Suspicious transaction reporting (STR):</strong> Operators must file STRs with Cambodia's Financial Intelligence Unit (CAFIU) for transactions exceeding $10,000 or displaying indicators of money laundering.</li>
    <li><strong>Record-keeping:</strong> All transaction and player identity records must be maintained for a minimum of 7 years.</li>
    <li><strong>Compliance officers:</strong> Each licensed operator must appoint a dedicated compliance officer, with Tier 3 operators required to have board-level compliance oversight.</li>
    <li><strong>Beneficial ownership transparency:</strong> Operators must disclose ultimate beneficial owners holding 10% or more of the entity.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The POGO Migration: From Philippines to Cambodia</h2>

  <p>The context for this framework is inseparable from the Philippine POGO saga. At its peak in 2019-2020, the Philippines hosted over 300 Philippine Offshore Gaming Operators, employing tens of thousands of foreign nationals (predominantly Chinese) and generating billions in revenue. However, the industry became synonymous with controversy: kidnappings, tax evasion, visa fraud, and links to organized crime led to growing political pressure for a ban.</p>

  <p>When the Philippine government officially banned POGOs in late 2024, operators faced a choice: shut down, convert to domestic-facing PIGO licenses, or relocate to another jurisdiction. An estimated 40-60 firms chose the third option, with Cambodia emerging as the primary destination due to its proximity, relatively permissive regulatory environment, and existing gaming infrastructure in Sihanoukville.</p>

  <p>The migration was not seamless. Many operators set up in Cambodia without formal licenses, operating in a gray zone that drew criticism from both the Cambodian government and international observers. The new CGC framework is, in many respects, a direct response to the problems created by this unregulated migration.</p>

  <h2>Regional Competition: Cambodia vs. Myanmar vs. UAE</h2>

  <p>Cambodia is not the only jurisdiction competing for post-POGO offshore gaming operators. Myanmar, particularly the Myawaddy special economic zone along the Thai border, has attracted operators willing to operate in a regulatory vacuum. The Myanmar gaming sector operates largely without formal licensing, and reports of human trafficking and forced labor in Myanmar gaming compounds have generated international condemnation.</p>

  <p>At the other end of the spectrum, the United Arab Emirates is developing a high-end gaming framework that targets resort-integrated, land-based operations rather than the online offshore model. The UAE approach, anchored by the planned Wynn Ras Al Khaimah resort, is positioned as a premium alternative that would attract a different class of operator than the POGO firms.</p>

