  <h2>Implications for the Philippines</h2>

  <p>Cambodia's new framework has direct implications for the Philippines. The formalization of offshore gaming in Cambodia creates a regulated competitor for Filipino-developed gaming talent, technology, and operational expertise. Several Philippine gaming technology companies and service providers have followed their clients to Cambodia, creating a brain drain of sorts from the Philippine gaming ecosystem.</p>

  <p>At the same time, the CGC framework validates the Philippines' decision to ban POGOs. If Cambodia can successfully regulate the operators that the Philippines expelled, it suggests that the fundamental problem was not offshore gaming itself but the lack of regulatory capacity and enforcement will in the Philippines. Conversely, if Cambodia struggles to control these operators, it will reinforce the Philippine narrative that the POGO model was inherently difficult to regulate.</p>

  <div class="pull-quote">
    <p>"The formalization of offshore gaming in Cambodia creates both a competitor and a validator for the Philippines. If Cambodia succeeds where PAGCOR struggled, the lesson is about regulatory architecture, not about the inherent risks of offshore gaming."</p>
    <cite>Regional gaming analyst</cite>
  </div>

  <h2>What Happens Next</h2>

  <p>The 180-day compliance window will be the immediate focus. Operators that have already established operations in Cambodia must now assess whether they can meet the capital and regulatory requirements of the applicable license tier. For smaller operators, the $1 million Tier 1 capital requirement may be achievable. For larger operations, the $10 million Tier 3 threshold represents a significant commitment but also grants broader operational scope.</p>

  <p>The CGC has indicated that it will publish additional regulatory guidance, including detailed AML implementation guidelines and technical standards for gaming platforms, within the first 60 days. The commission is also establishing a dedicated enforcement unit that will work with Cambodian law enforcement to identify and shut down unlicensed operations after the compliance deadline.</p>

